{"original": "Many of the country's grand railroad hotels were constructed from the 1880s through the first decade of the 20th century."}
{"original": "It was a fine time to be rich (before U.S. income tax) and a fine time to operate a luxury hotel (before cars changed travel patterns forever)."}
{"original": "The new hotels often also offered some less-expensive rooms to attract the rising middle class, Sandoval-Strausz said."}
{"original": "Though Canada has a slightly different railway-hotel history, lavish château-inspired hotels built by railroad companies started popping up there during the same period."}
{"original": "Fortunately for travelers today, some of the railroad hotels across the United States and Canada are still taking reservations:"}
{"original": "1. Grand Hotel, Mackinac Island, Michigan"}
{"original": "To meet a rising demand for suitable summer lodging on Michigan's scenic Mackinac Island, the Michigan Central Railroad, the Grand Rapids and Indiana Railroad, and the Detroit and Cleveland Steamship Navigation Company partnered in 1886 to form the Mackinac Island Hotel Co."}
{"original": "The wood-frame Grand Hotel opened the following year to guests who arrived by steamer and rail to sit and socialize on the hotel's impressive 660-foot-long front porch. Rates were $3 to $5 a night."}
{"original": "By the end of the 19th century, cars had arrived on the island but were quickly banned by a law that was finally strictly enforced in the 1930s. The island is still car-free today."}
{"original": "The Grand Hotel is open seasonally."}
