{"original": "1. The melt-up is over: One of Wall Street's biggest headaches could soon become its saving grace."}
{"original": "The bears growled for months about how expensive stocks became during the euphoria of late last year. And they had a point: Rarely in history have stocks been as pricey as they were during the recent boom."}
{"original": "Yet if there's a silver lining to the recent market chaos, it's that stocks no longer look absurdly overpriced. Heavy selling, driven largely by fears of trade wars and inflation, doused cold water on a market that had been overheating. The melt-up is over."}
{"original": "And that's not just because the Dow has fallen 2,500 points from its high point. It's that the market mayhem failed to shake the confidence of Wall Street."}
{"original": "Earnings estimates, a key indicator of stock prices, almost always decline each quarter as companies manage expectations lower (and then top those expectations anyway). Yet the opposite happened this time as analysts scrambled to assess the benefits of President Trump's corporate tax cuts."}
{"original": "Annual earnings estimates for S&P 500 companies jumped 7.1% during the first three months of the year — the most since FactSet (FDS) began keeping track in 1996. Meanwhile, the S&P 500 itself lost 1.2%."}
{"original": "That one-two combination caused Wall Street's favorite way of gauging stock valuations to drop — significantly."}
{"original": "The S&P 500 is now trading at 16.1 times projected earnings for the next year, according to FactSet. That's down dramatically from 18.6 in late January, when the Dow shot above 26,500. It's also back in line with the five-year average."}
{"original": "You have to take a step back and look at valuations, which have come down dramatically even as earnings forecasts have gone up, said Mary Ann Bartels, head of portfolio strategy at Merrill Lynch Wealth Management."}
{"original": "Corporate profits, buoyed by Trump's huge tax cuts and a strong economy, are projected to spike 18.5% this year."}
{"original": "Sam Stovall, chief investment strategist at CFRA Research, is encouraged by the more reasonable market valuations."}
{"original": "We believe the correction has likely run its course and is now working its jagged way back to breakeven, Stovall wrote to clients last week."}
{"original": "Of course, valuations are notoriously poor timing tools. Stocks that are pricey can stay that way, and vice versa. Consider how long it took for the market surge of 2017 to take a breather."}
{"original": "The key will be whether Corporate America delivers the blockbuster results that Wall Street is banking on. That would shift the attention away from the increasing turbulence out of Washington."}
{"original": "We're expecting earnings to be really strong, Bartels said. If they are, we can finally recover from this correction."}
