{"original": "It's hard to believe that Prince -- who was famously meticulous about maintaining control over his name and music -- may have died without a will."}
{"original": "That leaves open the question of who will inherit his millions, his record label and his unreleased songs."}
{"original": "So what happens to someone's estate if they didn't make their wishes known in writing?"}
{"original": "[A will] is your voice and lets you decide where things go and who you want to carry these things out, said David DuFault, an estate planning attorney at Sodoma Law in Charlotte, North Carolina."}
{"original": "If you die without one, you cede control to the state where you lived. Its laws will determine who your heirs will be and the state will choose the executor of your estate."}
{"original": "While inheritance laws differ from state to state, they generally favor spouses, registered domestic partners and blood relatives as heirs."}
{"original": "Unmarried partners, friends, and charities get nothing, according to legal guide publisher NOLO."}
{"original": "In Prince's case, he was divorced and he didn't have any surviving children. Plus, both his parents had already died. So under Minnesota law, unless someone finds a will or a trust that he created, his estate will go to his sister and his half-siblings."}
{"original": "Related: Special administrator appointed for Prince's estate"}
{"original": "There are, however, some assets that pass to people of your choosing even if you don't leave a will. If you had a life insurance policy with designated beneficiaries, those people will get those proceeds without state interference, DuFault noted. The same is usually true with your retirement accounts."}
{"original": "But if you don't designate beneficiaries, all proceeds will roll into your estate and be distributed according to state rules."}
{"original": "A will is also extremely important for parents, because it's the primary instrument by which you name the guardian of your minor children, and otherwise provide protections for them when you're gone, said estate planning attorney Jeffrey Molever of JUX law firm in Minneapolis."}
{"original": "Without a will, the court will appoint their guardian. The judge will gather as much information as possible about the children, their family circumstances, and the deceased parents' wishes and try to make a good decision. The primary rule is that the judge must always act in the best interests of the children, according to NOLO."}
{"original": "Still that doesn't mean the court will pick the person you would want to care for your kids."}
{"original": "The good news is most Americans will not be hit by the federal estate tax, since the first $5.45 million of an estate is exempt. The remainder would be taxed at rates up to 40%."}
{"original": "Related: Money essentials on wills and trusts"}
{"original": "But many states have their own estate tax. And typically their exemption levels are much lower than Uncle Sam's. In Minnesota, for instance, any estate worth more than $1.6 million this year will be taxed at rates as high as 16%."}
{"original": "Without a will, you could lose out on important tax benefits, such as the marital deduction, which lets your surviving spouse inherit your whole estate tax-free."}
{"original": "In North Carolina, for instance, if you die without a will, your estate will be divided by your spouse and your kids according to a state formula, DuFault said. That could subject portions of your estate to taxes."}
{"original": "So if you think you'll have a taxable estate, a will is especially important."}
{"original": "Why the Gilet Jaunes are going after Macron"}
{"original": "A prominent figure in France's gilets jaunes, or yellow vest, movement was seriously wounded during a protest in Paris on Saturday."}
{"original": "Jerome Rodrigues, a self-described pacifist, was injured in his right eye by a projectile hurled towards him, allegedly by police."}
{"original": "In an interview with French broadcaster LCI on Sunday, Rodrigues said that he had stayed in Paris' Place de la Bastille to encourage fellow yellow vest demonstrators to leave the area as skirmishes between the Black Bloc – another group of protesters often associated with anarchy and violent skirmishes – and the police, escalated."}
{"original": "Rodrigues' lawyer Philippe de Veulle told CNN affiliate BFM TV that he believes that a flash ball – a controversial less lethal hand-held weapon launcher deployed by French police in riots – injured him."}
{"original": "French police said the watchdog agency the General Inspectorate of National Police (IGPN) had launched an investigation into the case of an injured man rescued on Bastille Square."}
{"original": "Rodrigues's lawyer said he had evidence to give the IGPN."}
{"original": "I have material elements in the sense that it's a Flash Ball shot. The Flash Ball will be handed over to the IGPN Divisional Commissioner, who contacted my client's sister last night, de Veulle told BFM TV."}
{"original": "Flash Ball is a French-made trademarked projectile whose manufacturer, Verney-Carron Security, calls it a non-lethal 44mm-gauge weapon… versatile, adaptable, but always effective."}
{"original": "The incident was captured by Rodrigues, as he was livestreaming the protest, on his Facebook page. The video has been watched over 1.4M times and shared by 67,000 users."}
{"original": "Shortly after the incident, Rodrigues posted a photo to his Facebook account that said: I am going to lose my eye, fam."}
{"original": "The protests – named after the yellow high-visibility jackets French motorists must carry in their vehicles – started November 17 in reaction to an eco-tax on gas but have since morphed into broader demonstrations against President Emmanuel Macron and his government."}
{"original": "Last month, a pressurized Macron pledged to increase the minimum wage and get rid of new pension taxes. But the move has done little to appease the anger felt by some hard-core protesters."}
{"original": "Saturday marked the 11th consecutive week of the demonstrations. A French Interior Ministry spokesperson told CNN that approximately 69,000 people marched on Saturday in solidarity with the yellow vest movement, including 4,000 protesters in Paris."}
{"original": "I am a hyper pacifist, I do not want anyone to get hurt, Rodrigues said. I was there to make sure my little yellow guys could get out of this hell."}
{"original": "Rodrigues gave further details on the incident, saying that that he had been to the hospital and awaits further guidance from doctors regarding his injury."}
{"original": "It's very painful. I'm waiting for the doctors to come and tell me what it is. It's my right eye, and I think I stayed in the operating room for seven or eight hours, Rodrigues said."}
{"original": "Rodrigues is planning on filing a complaint to the police, LCI reported."}
{"original": "I was deliberately targeted. I am a figure of the movement, at least in the Paris protests, and police pointed their fingers at me many times during previous demonstrations, so I think they knew very well who they were shooting at, Rodrigues told BFM TV Sunday."}
{"original": "Ten people have died in connection with the protests, with most deaths taking place in traffic accidents related to blockades in November and December."}
{"original": "On Sunday, 10,500 people marched in the French capital for the so-called foulards rouges or red scarfs protest, in opposition to the ongoing yellow vest demonstrations, according to the Paris Police Department."}
{"original": "CNN's Martin Goillandeau, Ben Marcus and Nada Bashir contributed to this report."}
