{"original": "Do you know why money gets taken out of your paycheck?"}
{"original": "If you don't, you're not alone. Nearly 64 million people are perplexed by their pay stubs, including half of younger workers, according to a recent study from Kronos Incorporated."}
{"original": "Knowing where your hard-earned money goes can empower you to make smart decisions about taxes, retirement savings, health care and even potential paycheck errors."}
{"original": "Your gross pay is how much money you earned each pay period. It is likely to be quite a bit more than the amount that is actually deposited into your bank account (that's your net pay)."}
{"original": "If you're an hourly employee you'll see your per-hour rate as well as any overtime you earned. Salaried workers may see the total annual compensation divided by the number of paychecks you'll get in the year. You'll probably also see the number of hours you've worked in the pay period."}
{"original": "Most paychecks will also show you your net pay to date (rendered Net YTD). That's how much money you've taken home so far this year. Your net pay -- whether annually or for the pay period -- is the number you should use when you start a budget."}
{"original": "Related: How to become financially independent in 5 years"}
{"original": "Until you get up and running at a new job it can be hard to figure out how much will be taken out each week and what you'll end up taking home. Here's a calculator to help you estimate your net pay."}
