{"original": "Contributions to Roth IRAs are not tax deductible, but you can withdraw the money in retirement tax free. Plus you can access the money you put in (not your investment gains) at any time, without penalty."}
{"original": "Related: Millennials explain why they have nothing saved for retirement"}
{"original": "Compared to other retirement accounts, Traditional and Roth IRAs have low contribution limits. Both currently allow you to save up to $5,500 annually (or up to $6,500 if you're 50 or older). Even if you contribute the max each year, you probably won't have enough to fund a comfortable retirement without saving elsewhere."}
{"original": "To save extra money, the best thing is to use a plain old brokerage account, said Adam."}
{"original": "You won't get a tax deduction, but you'll be able to access your money at any time to use for any reason."}
