{"original": "A suspension lets the U.S. Treasury borrow as needed to satisfy the country's legal obligations in full and on time. Those obligations include everything from veteran benefits and military paychecks to contractor fees and bills incurred by all federal programs."}
{"original": "Once the suspension ends, the amount borrowed during the suspension period will be added to the legal debt limit."}
{"original": "Politically, it's easier to pass a suspension, said Shai Akabas, director of economic policy at the Bipartisan Policy Center."}
