{"original": "Like the riot, the legal liability for Trump's call to Georgia election officials will turn on his statements. Trump called the Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger, a Republican, imploring him to find 11,780 votes to give him the edge to overturn the election. It followed a call in December in which Trump told a Georgia elections investigator to search for dishonesty in the 2020 presidential election, telling the individual that the investigation was of national importance, according to a source with knowledge of the call."}
{"original": "The calls have prompted letters and calls for state and federal investigations into Trump's conduct. It isn't clear if there is an active investigation. Former prosecutors say the outreach is worth federal prosecutors' scrutiny even if Trump wasn't successful because of the intimidation and threats the officials have faced."}
{"original": "As the end of Trump's presidency nears, sources tell CNN Trump has considered pardoning himself , his family members and other allies from federal charges. Lawyers say it is not clear whether a self-pardon would hold up in court, but a presidential pardon has no bearing on state investigations."}
