{"original": "Which begs the question: Why did the Fed raise rates in September and December in the first place? There were almost seven million open jobs in November last year, and 2018 saw the lowest unemployment rate since the 1960s and is on track to see real economic growth of more than 3% for the first time since 2005. Average hourly pay was up. And inflation of consumer prices even before the rate hikes have been pretty flat, growing at about 1% to 2%, which is right in the sweet zone that the Fed targets."}
