{"original": "Under World Trade Organization rules we have agreed to limit our tariffs on products to bound rates, and any increase above those rates violates WTO rules."}
{"original": "We also have most favored nation commitments, which precludes WTO members from treating one WTO member worse than other members. (There are exceptions to this rule, including preferential treatment in the context of free trade agreements such as NAFTA.)"}
{"original": "Trump's proposed tax increase on Mexican products clearly violates both of those treaty commitments."}
{"original": "The North American Free Trade Agreement has similar prohibitions, including its Article 302, which prohibits the United States from increas(ing) any customs duty."}
{"original": "Mexico could sue the United States before the WTO to challenge the illegal tax. Mexico would be authorized to impose retaliatory duties equal to the harm caused by the violation. (Mexico could sue under NAFTA as well, and when it succeeds, suspend US NAFTA benefits.)"}
